  "lifePath": {
    "below-upper-secondary": {
      "early": [
        "You grew up in a small flat on the edge of Narva. Winters meant damp walls and a shared courtyard where the older kids taught you Russian swear words before you learned the Estonian ones.",
        "Home was a wooden house outside J\u00f5hvi. Your mother worked double shifts; you learned early how to heat the stove and keep quiet when the adults were tired.",
        "You spent summers with grandparents near Sillam\u00e4e, picking berries for cash while your parents chased work farther west."
      ],
      "school": [
        "School never quite stuck. By fifteen you were skipping afternoons to help a cousin on a construction site, promising yourself you'd go back next term.",
        "You finished basic school and tried vocational training in Kohtla-J\u00e4rve, then dropped out when the family needed another wage.",
        "Teachers pushed you toward a trade. You lasted a year at a workshop, then left with a toolkit and no certificate."
      ],
      "work": [
        "You took whatever paid: warehouse shifts in Tallinn, then seasonal work on site, always one month ahead of the rent.",
        "A relative got you onto a road crew. The money was better than school had ever promised, until your back started complaining.",
        "You drove vans between Ida-Viru and the capital, living out of a borrowed room and sending cash home when you could."
      ],
      "family": [
        "You moved in with someone you met at work before either of you had a steady plan. The first child arrived sooner than the savings did.",
        "Family meant a small rented flat, a partner on night shifts, and weekends spent patching what broke before it got expensive.",
        "You married young, split the bills with relatives nearby, and measured adulthood in overdue invoices and birthday cakes."
      ],
      "midlife": [
        "By your forties the early years showed: thinner health, thinner savings, and a calendar built around whoever would still hire you.",
        "Friends from school had settled. You were still trading long hours for short security, watching the gap widen.",
        "Midlife looked like another temporary contract, a cigarette break in a parking lot, and the quiet hope that the kids would finish school properly."
      ]
    },
    "upper-secondary": {
      "early": [
